<file path="docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md">
  1: # Label Resolution Guide (L6 Pattern)
  2: 
  3: ## Overview
  4: 
  5: The L6 refactoring introduces dynamic label ID resolution, eliminating hardcoded account-specific label IDs (e.g., `Label_5`, `Label_18`) in Gmail scripts.
  6: 
  7: ## Pattern
  8: 
  9: ### Before (Hardcoded)
 10: ```javascript
 11: import { createGmailClient } from './lib/gmail-client.mjs';
 12: 
 13: async function myScript() {
 14:   const gmail = createGmailClient();
 15:   const labelId = 'Label_7'; // Account-specific, breaks on other accounts
 16:   const messages = await gmail.users.messages.list({
 17:     userId: 'me',
 18:     labelIds: [labelId],
 19:   });
 20: }
 21: ```
 22: 
 23: ### After (Dynamic Resolution)
 24: ```javascript
 25: import { createGmailClient } from './lib/gmail-client.mjs';
 26: import { buildLabelCache } from './lib/gmail-label-utils.mjs';
 27: 
 28: async function myScript() {
 29:   const gmail = createGmailClient();
 30: 
 31:   try {
 32:     const labelCache = await buildLabelCache(gmail);
 33:     const labelId = labelCache.get('Events/Community'); // or your label name
 34: 
 35:     if (!labelId) {
 36:       console.error('❌ Events/Community label not found');
 37:       process.exit(1);
 38:     }
 39: 
 40:     const messages = await gmail.users.messages.list({
 41:       userId: 'me',
 42:       labelIds: [labelId],
 43:     });
 44:   } catch (error) {
 45:     console.error('❌ Error:', error.message);
 46:     process.exit(1);
 47:   }
 48: }
 49: ```
 50: 
 51: ## Steps to Refactor
 52: 
 53: 1. **Add import** at top of file:
 54:    ```javascript
 55:    import { buildLabelCache } from './lib/gmail-label-utils.mjs';
 56:    ```
 57: 
 58: 2. **Build label cache** in your try block:
 59:    ```javascript
 60:    const labelCache = await buildLabelCache(gmail);
 61:    ```
 62: 
 63: 3. **Resolve label ID** by name instead of hardcoded value:
 64:    ```javascript
 65:    // Before:
 66:    const labelId = 'Label_7';
 67: 
 68:    // After:
 69:    const labelId = labelCache.get('Your/Label/Name');
 70:    if (!labelId) {
 71:      console.error('❌ Your/Label/Name not found');
 72:      process.exit(1);
 73:    }
 74:    ```
 75: 
 76: 4. **Handle multiple possible names** (if label name might vary):
 77:    ```javascript
 78:    const labelId = labelCache.get('Events/Workshops') ||
 79:                    labelCache.get('Workshops');
 80:    ```
 81: 
 82: ## Available Label Resolution Functions
 83: 
 84: - **`buildLabelCache(gmail)`** - Fetch all labels once at startup
 85:   - Returns: `Map<string, string>` of label names to IDs
 86:   - Use: Fast lookups within same script execution
 87: 
 88: - **`resolveLabelId(gmail, labelName, labelCache)`** - Single label lookup with caching
 89:   - Use: When you need a specific label
 90:   - Cache miss triggers rebuild
 91: 
 92: - **`resolveLabelIds(gmail, labelNames)`** - Batch label resolution
 93:   - Use: When resolving multiple labels at once
 94:   - Returns: `Map<string, string>` of found labels
 95: 
 96: ## Benefits
 97: 
 98: ✅ **Portable** - Works across different Gmail accounts with different label hierarchies
 99: ✅ **Reliable** - Fails explicitly if label not found (instead of silently)
100: ✅ **Maintainable** - No magic numbers, clear intent
101: ✅ **Consistent** - Follows established pattern across scripts
102: 
103: ## Examples
104: 
105: ### Example 1: Single Label Resolution
106: ```javascript
107: const labelCache = await buildLabelCache(gmail);
108: const communityId = labelCache.get('Events/Community');
109: ```
110: 
111: ### Example 2: Multiple Label Fallbacks
112: ```javascript
113: const labelCache = await buildLabelCache(gmail);
114: const ccvId = labelCache.get('Events/Invitations/Community Services/Capital City Village') ||
115:               labelCache.get('Services/Capital City Village') ||
116:               labelCache.get('Capital City Village');
117: ```
118: 
119: ### Example 3: Batch Resolution
120: ```javascript
121: import { resolveLabelIds } from './lib/gmail-label-utils.mjs';
122: 
123: const labelNames = ['Events/Community', 'Services/Important'];
124: const resolved = await resolveLabelIds(gmail, labelNames);
125: 
126: const communityId = resolved.get('Events/Community');
127: const importantId = resolved.get('Services/Important');
128: ```
129: 
130: ## Finding Your Label Names
131: 
132: To find the correct label names for your account:
133: 
134: 1. **List all labels** in any refactored script:
135:    ```javascript
136:    const labelCache = await buildLabelCache(gmail);
137:    for (const [name, id] of labelCache) {
138:      console.log(`${name} → ${id}`);
139:    }
140:    ```
141: 
142: 2. **Use Gmail UI** - See label hierarchy in Gmail settings
143: 
144: 3. **Comment mapping** - Document the hardcoded ID with its name:
145:    ```javascript
146:    // Label_7 → Newsletters/Subject-Based
147:    ```
148: 
149: ## Scripts Already Using L6
150: 
151: - ✅ `create-all-sublabels.mjs` - Dynamic resolution for workshop/community labels
152: - ✅ `analyze-community-events.mjs` - Events/Community label resolution
153: 
154: ## Contributing
155: 
156: When refactoring new scripts:
157: 1. Add buildLabelCache import
158: 2. Document original label names in comments
159: 3. Use fallback lookups if label name might vary
160: 4. Test script works with the resolved label ID
161: 5. Commit with `refactor(L6-extended):` prefix
</file>

<file path="docs/SIMPLE_RRULE_INTEGRATION.md">
  1: # Simple RRule Integration
  2: 
  3: ## Overview
  4: `simple-rrule` (v1.8.1) has been installed to provide TypeScript-first RRULE parsing, validation, and expansion capabilities.
  5: 
  6: ## Installation Changes
  7: - **Package**: `simple-rrule@^1.8.1` added to `dependencies`
  8: - **Zod upgrade**: Upgraded from `^3.22.4` to `^4.x` (simple-rrule requires zod@>=4)
  9: - **Installation**: Used `--legacy-peer-deps` due to openai's optional zod@^3.x peer dependency
 10: 
 11: ## What simple-rrule Provides
 12: 
 13: ### Core Functions
 14: ```typescript
 15: // Parse RRULE strings
 16: parseRecurrenceFromString(rruleString) -> IRrule | undefined
 17: 
 18: // Serialize to RRULE
 19: getRRuleString(rule) -> string
 20: 
 21: // Expand rules to actual dates
 22: expandRRuleFromString(rruleString, startDate, endDate) -> IExpandResult
 23: expandRRule(rule, startDate, endDate) -> IExpandResult
 24: 
 25: // Date utilities
 26: toRRuleDateString(date) -> string    // Format for RRULE UNTIL clauses
 27: fromRruleDateStringToDate(str) -> Date
 28: ```
 29: 
 30: ### IRrule Object Structure
 31: ```typescript
 32: {
 33:   dtStart: string;           // ISO 8601 datetime
 34:   dtEnd: string;             // ISO 8601 datetime
 35:   frequency: 'DAILY' | 'WEEKLY' | 'MONTHLY' | 'YEARLY' | ...;
 36:   interval: number;          // e.g., every 2 weeks
 37:   count?: number;            // Limit occurrences
 38:   until?: string;            // UNTIL date (ISO format)
 39:   byDay: string;             // 'MO,WE,FR', etc.
 40:   byMonth: number;           // Month number
 41:   byMonthDay: number;        // Day of month
 42:   bySetPos: number;          // Position in set
 43:   wkst: 'SU' | 'MO' | ...;   // Week start day
 44: }
 45: ```
 46: 
 47: ## Migration Path
 48: 
 49: ### Current Setup (Keeps Existing Code)
 50: Our custom `RRULE_PATTERNS` regex-based approach is kept for now:
 51: - `stripUntilAndCount()` - removes UNTIL/COUNT clauses
 52: - `buildUntilClause()` - constructs UNTIL clauses
 53: - `isRRuleString()` - detects RRULE vs EXDATE/RDATE
 54: 
 55: **Why**: These are simple string operations that don't require full parsing. The regex approach is fast and doesn't need the overhead of parsing.
 56: 
 57: ### New Adapter (simple-rrule-adapter.ts)
 58: For future enhancements, use the adapter module:
 59: ```typescript
 60: import {
 61:   parseRRule,           // Parse RRULE string
 62:   serializeRRule,       // Convert back to string
 63:   expandRRuleToDateRange,  // Get all occurrences
 64:   setRRuleUntil,        // Update UNTIL
 65:   clearRRuleConstraints  // Remove COUNT/UNTIL
 66: } from './simple-rrule-adapter.js';
 67: ```
 68: 
 69: ### Use Cases for Replacement
 70: 
 71: **When to use simple-rrule**:
 72: - Validating complex RRULE strings
 73: - Expanding rules to find all occurrences
 74: - Modifying rule objects and serializing
 75: - Handling edge cases (leap years, DST, month boundaries)
 76: 
 77: **When to keep regex**:
 78: - Simple string manipulations (strip/build clauses)
 79: - Performance-critical paths (parsing on every update)
 80: - Pattern matching against EXDATE/RDATE
 81: 
 82: ## Example Usage
 83: 
 84: ```typescript
 85: import { expandRRuleToDateRange } from './utils/simple-rrule-adapter.js';
 86: 
 87: // Get all daily occurrences in a date range
 88: const rrule = 'RRULE:FREQ=DAILY;COUNT=7;DTSTART=20260324T100000Z';
 89: const dates = expandRRuleToDateRange(
 90:   rrule,
 91:   new Date('2026-03-24'),
 92:   new Date('2026-04-01')
 93: );
 94: 
 95: console.log(dates);
 96: // [2026-03-24, 2026-03-25, 2026-03-26, ...]
 97: ```
 98: 
 99: ## Testing
100: The installation was verified with:
101: ```javascript
102: parseRecurrenceFromString('RRULE:FREQ=DAILY;COUNT=3')
103: // Successfully parses and returns IRrule object
104: 
105: expandRRuleFromString(rruleString, start, end)
106: // Successfully expands to 3 dates
107: ```
108: 
109: ## Known Limitations
110: - `simple-rrule` does not support TZ (timezone) in RRULE
111: - Our custom UNTIL date formatting (basic ISO: `YYYYMMDDTHHMMSSZ`) is preserved for Google Calendar compatibility
112: - The library works with ISO 8601 dates; careful conversion needed for all-day events
113: 
114: ## Next Steps
115: 1. **Gradual migration**: Use adapter for RecurringEventHelpers validation
116: 2. **Validation layer**: Wrap parseRRule to validate calendar compatibility
117: 3. **Testing**: Add unit tests for edge cases with simple-rrule
118: 4. **Documentation**: Update RecurringEventHelpers docs with examples
</file>

<file path="docs/deployment.md">
  1: # Deployment Guide
  2: 
  3: This guide covers deploying the Google Calendar MCP Server for remote access via HTTP transport.
  4: 
  5: ## Transport Modes
  6: 
  7: ### stdio Transport (Default)
  8: - Local use only
  9: - Direct communication with Claude Desktop
 10: - No network exposure
 11: - Automatic authentication handling
 12: 
 13: ### HTTP Transport
 14: - Remote deployment capable
 15: - Server-Sent Events (SSE) for real-time communication
 16: - Built-in security features
 17: - Suitable for cloud deployment
 18: 
 19: ## HTTP Server Features
 20: 
 21: - ✅ **CORS Support**: Basic cross-origin access support
 22: - ✅ **Health Monitoring**: Basic health check endpoint
 23: - ✅ **Graceful Shutdown**: Proper resource cleanup
 24: - ✅ **Origin Validation**: DNS rebinding protection
 25: 
 26: ## Local HTTP Deployment
 27: 
 28: ### Basic HTTP Server
 29: 
 30: ```bash
 31: # Start on localhost only (default port 3000)
 32: npm run start:http
 33: ```
 34: 
 35: ### Public HTTP Server
 36: 
 37: ```bash
 38: # Listen on all interfaces (0.0.0.0)
 39: npm run start:http:public
 40: ```
 41: 
 42: ### Environment Variables
 43: 
 44: ```bash
 45: PORT=3000                    # Server port
 46: HOST=localhost              # Bind address
 47: TRANSPORT=http              # Transport mode
 48: ```
 49: 
 50: ## Cloud Deployment
 51: 
 52: ### Google Cloud Run
 53: 
 54: ```bash
 55: # Build and push image
 56: gcloud builds submit --tag gcr.io/PROJECT-ID/calendar-mcp
 57: 
 58: # Deploy
 59: gcloud run deploy calendar-mcp \
 60:   --image gcr.io/PROJECT-ID/calendar-mcp \
 61:   --platform managed \
 62:   --region us-central1 \
 63:   --allow-unauthenticated \
 64:   --set-env-vars="TRANSPORT=http"
 65: ```
 66: 
 67: ### AWS ECS
 68: 
 69: 1. Push image to ECR
 70: 2. Create task definition with environment variables
 71: 3. Deploy service with ALB
 72: 
 73: ### Heroku
 74: 
 75: ```bash
 76: # Create app
 77: heroku create your-calendar-mcp
 78: 
 79: # Set buildpack
 80: heroku buildpacks:set heroku/nodejs
 81: 
 82: # Configure
 83: heroku config:set TRANSPORT=http
 84: heroku config:set GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS=./gcp-oauth.keys.json
 85: 
 86: # Deploy
 87: git push heroku main
 88: ```
 89: 
 90: ## Security Configuration
 91: 
 92: ### HTTPS/TLS
 93: 
 94: Always use HTTPS in production:
 95: 
 96: 1. **Behind a Reverse Proxy** (Recommended)
 97:    ```nginx
 98:    server {
 99:        listen 443 ssl;
100:        server_name calendar-mcp.example.com;
101:        
102:        ssl_certificate /path/to/cert.pem;
103:        ssl_certificate_key /path/to/key.pem;
104:        
105:        location / {
106:            proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
107:            proxy_http_version 1.1;
108:            proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
109:            proxy_set_header Connection '';
110:            proxy_set_header Host $host;
111:            proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
112:        }
113:    }
114:    ```
115: 
116: 2. **Direct TLS** (Not built-in)
117:    For TLS support, use a reverse proxy like nginx or a cloud load balancer with SSL termination.
118: 
119: 
120: ### Authentication Flow
121: 
122: 1. Client connects to HTTP endpoint
123: 2. Server redirects to Google OAuth
124: 3. User authenticates with Google
125: 4. Server stores tokens securely
126: 5. Client receives session token
127: 6. All requests use session token
128: 
129: ## Monitoring
130: 
131: ### Health Checks
132: 
133: ```bash
134: # Health check
135: curl http://localhost:3000/health
136: ```
137: 
138: ### Logging
139: 
140: ```bash
141: # Enable debug logging
142: DEBUG=mcp:* npm run start:http
143: 
144: # JSON logging for production
145: NODE_ENV=production npm run start:http
146: ```
147: 
148: 
149: ## Production Checklist
150: 
151: **OAuth App Setup:**
152: - [ ] **Publish OAuth app to production in Google Cloud Console**
153: - [ ] **Set up proper redirect URIs for your domain**
154: - [ ] **Use production OAuth credentials (not test/development)**
155: - [ ] **Consider submitting for verification to remove user warnings**
156: 
157: **Infrastructure:**
158: - [ ] Use HTTPS/TLS encryption
159: - [ ] Configure reverse proxy for production
160: - [ ] Set up SSL termination
161: - [ ] Set up monitoring/alerting for authentication failures
162: - [ ] Configure log aggregation
163: - [ ] Implement backup strategy for token storage
164: - [ ] Test disaster recovery and re-authentication procedures
165: - [ ] Review security headers
166: - [ ] Enable graceful shutdown
167: 
168: **Note**: The 7-day token expiration is resolved by publishing your OAuth app to production in Google Cloud Console.
169: 
170: ## Troubleshooting
171: 
172: ### Connection Issues
173: - Check firewall rules
174: - Verify CORS configuration
175: - Test with curl first
176: 
177: ### Authentication Failures
178: - Ensure credentials are accessible
179: - Check token permissions
180: - Verify redirect URIs
181: 
182: ### Performance Problems
183: - Enable caching headers
184: - Use CDN for static assets
185: - Monitor memory usage
186: 
187: See [Troubleshooting Guide](troubleshooting.md) for more solutions.
</file>

