  1: # Google Calendar & Gmail MCP Server
  2: 
  3: A Model Context Protocol (MCP) server that provides Google Calendar and Gmail integration for AI assistants like Claude.
  4: 
  5: ## Features
  6: 
  7: ### Calendar
  8: - **Multi-Calendar Support**: List events from multiple calendars simultaneously
  9: - **Event Management**: Create, update, delete, and search calendar events
 10: - **Recurring Events**: Advanced modification capabilities for recurring events
 11: - **Free/Busy Queries**: Check availability across calendars
 12: - **Smart Scheduling**: Natural language understanding for dates and times
 13: - **Inteligent Import**: Add calendar events from images, PDFs or web links
 14: 
 15: ### Gmail
 16: - **Message Search**: Query Gmail with flexible search filters (is:unread, from:, subject:, etc.)
 17: - **Profile Management**: Get account information (message count, thread count, email address)
 18: - **Multi-Account Support**: Use multiple Gmail accounts with separate OAuth tokens
 19: 
 20: ## Recent Updates (v1.4.9)
 21: 
 22: **Performance & Reliability:**
 23: - 🚀 Dynamic label ID resolution (L6) - Scripts now work across accounts with different label hierarchies
 24: - ⚡ Sequential API optimization - ~500ms latency reduction per operation
 25: - 📦 Batch filter operations - 10-100x speedup for bulk Gmail tasks
 26: 
 27: **Tooling & Infrastructure:**
 28: - ✅ Comprehensive label resolution guide ([docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md](docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md))
 29: - 🧪 Parametrized test expansion (25 → 30+ test cases)
 30: - 📋 New changelog system ([docs/changelog/](docs/changelog/)) tracking all improvements
 31: 
 32: **Testing:**
 33: - 492/494 tests passing (99.6%)
 34: - Reduced technical debt with shared utilities in `lib/gmail-*.mjs`
 35: - CLAUDE.md updated with latest patterns and utilities
 36: 
 37: See [CHANGELOG](docs/CHANGELOG.md) for complete v1.4.9 release notes.
 38: 
 39: ## Quick Start
 40: 
 41: ### Prerequisites
 42: 
 43: 1. A Google Cloud project with the Calendar API enabled
 44: 2. OAuth 2.0 credentials (Desktop app type)
 45: 
 46: ### Google Cloud Setup
 47: 
 48: 1. Go to the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com)
 49: 2. Create a new project or select an existing one.
 50: 3. Enable the [Google Calendar API](https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/calendar-json.googleapis.com) for your project. Ensure that the right project is selected from the top bar before enabling the API.
 51: 4. Create OAuth 2.0 credentials:
 52:    - Go to Credentials
 53:    - Click "Create Credentials" > "OAuth client ID"
 54:    - Choose "User data" for the type of data that the app will be accessing
 55:    - Add your app name and contact information
 56:    - Add the following scopes (optional):
 57:      - `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events` and `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar`
 58:    - Select "Desktop app" as the application type (Important!)
 59:    - Save the auth key, you'll need to add its path to the JSON in the next step
 60:    - Add your email address as a test user under the [Audience screen](https://console.cloud.google.com/auth/audience)
 61:       - Note: it might take a few minutes for the test user to be added. The OAuth consent will not allow you to proceed until the test user has propagated.
 62:       - Note about test mode: While an app is in test mode the auth tokens will expire after 1 week and need to be refreshed (see Re-authentication section below).
 63: 
 64: ### Installation
 65: 
 66: **Option 1: Use with npx (Recommended)**
 67: 
 68: Add to your Claude Desktop configuration:
 69: 
 70: **macOS**: `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json`
 71: **Windows**: `%APPDATA%\Claude\claude_desktop_config.json`
 72: ```json
 73: {
 74:   "mcpServers": {
 75:     "google-calendar": {
 76:       "command": "npx",
 77:       "args": ["@cocal/google-calendar-mcp"],
 78:       "env": {
 79:         "GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS": "/path/to/your/gcp-oauth.keys.json"
 80:       }
 81:     }
 82:   }
 83: }
 84: ```
 85: 
 86: **⚠️ Important Note for npx Users**: When using npx, you **must** specify the credentials file path using the `GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS` environment variable.
 87: 
 88: **Option 2: Local Installation**
 89: 
 90: ```bash
 91: git clone https://github.com/nspady/google-calendar-mcp.git
 92: cd google-calendar-mcp
 93: npm install
 94: npm run build
 95: ```
 96: 
 97: Then add to Claude Desktop config using the local path or by specifying the path with the `GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS` environment variable.
 98: 
 99: ### First Run
100: 
101: 1. Start Claude Desktop
102: 2. The server will prompt for authentication on first use
103: 3. Complete the OAuth flow in your browser
104: 4. You're ready to use calendar features!
105: 
106: ### Multi-Account Support (Test Mode)
107: 
108: This server supports multiple Google accounts in test mode with automatic token management.
109: 
110: **Setup both accounts:**
111: 
112: Account 1 (Initial):
113: ```bash
114: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
115: export CALENDARMCP_TOKEN_PATH=~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens.json
116: npm run auth
117: ```
118: 
119: Account 2 (Same file, different account key):
120: ```bash
121: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
122: export CALENDARMCP_TOKEN_PATH=~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens.json
123: npm run auth  # Authenticates second account in same tokens.json
124: ```
125: 
126: **Verify both accounts:**
127: ```bash
128: export GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS="./credentials.json"
129: npm run verify-tokens
130: ```
131: 
132: Outputs token status, expiry times, and account validity for all authenticated accounts.
133: 
134: **Important Notes:**
135: - Both accounts stored in single `tokens.json` file with separate keys
136: - Tokens expire after 7 days in test mode (Google requirement)
137: - TokenManager auto-refreshes tokens 5 minutes before expiry
138: - Set `ACCOUNT_MODE` environment variable before running the server to select which account is active
139: 
140: ### Re-authentication
141: 
142: If you're in test mode (default), tokens expire after 7 days. If you are using a client like Claude Desktop it should open up a browser window to automatically re-auth. However, if you see authentication errors you can also resolve by following these steps:
143: 
144: **For npx users:**
145: ```bash
146: export GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS="/path/to/your/gcp-oauth.keys.json"
147: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
148: npx @cocal/google-calendar-mcp auth
149: ```
150: 
151: **For local installation:**
152: ```bash
153: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
154: npm run auth
155: ```
156: 
157: **To avoid weekly re-authentication**, publish your app to production mode (without verification):
158: 1. Go to Google Cloud Console → "APIs & Services" → "OAuth consent screen"
159: 2. Click "PUBLISH APP" and confirm
160: 3. Your tokens will no longer expire after 7 days but Google will show a more threatning warning when connecting to the app about it being unverified.
161: 
162: See [Authentication Guide](docs/authentication.md#moving-to-production-mode-recommended) for details.
163: 
164: ### Gmail OAuth Setup
165: 
166: To enable Gmail features, authenticate with Gmail scopes:
167: 
168: ```bash
169: # Using the provided auth script
170: node auth-gmail.mjs
171: ```
172: 
173: This will:
174: 1. Open your browser for OAuth authentication
175: 2. Request Gmail access (read and modify permissions)
176: 3. Save tokens to `~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens-gmail.json`
177: 
178: **Quick Check:**
179: ```bash
180: # Check unread message count
181: node check-gmail.mjs
182: ```
183: 
184: **Important Notes:**
185: - Gmail and Calendar tokens are stored separately
186: - Gmail scopes: `gmail.readonly`, `gmail.modify`
187: - Tokens expire after 7 days in test mode
188: - Re-authenticate as needed with `node auth-gmail.mjs`
189: 
190: ### Email Organization & Filtering Scripts
191: 
192: Automated scripts for organizing and filtering large volumes of Gmail with focus on correctness and efficiency.
193: 
194: **Management Scripts:** (use shared `createGmailClient()` for OAuth, error handling, and multi-account support)
195: - `list-unread-emails.mjs` - Categorize and summarize unread emails by label/sender patterns; clean fallback categorization
196: - `summarize-remaining.mjs` - Summary of uncategorized/remaining unread emails (internal work, forums, misc); parallel fetching
197: - `describe-internal.mjs` - Detailed breakdown of internal team emails with subjects and dates; hardcoded summary removed
198: - `apply-filters-to-unread.mjs` - Apply existing filters to current unread emails
199: - `create-remaining-filters.mjs` - Batch create filters for multiple categories (Product Updates, Communities, Services)
200: 
201: **Specialized Filters:**
202: - `create-billing-filter.mjs` - Smart billing filter with conditional rate-limit detection
203: - `create-signoz-filter.mjs` - Archive SigNoz monitoring alerts automatically
204: - `create-dmarc-filter.mjs` - Organize DMARC authentication reports
205: - `create-eventbrite-filter.mjs` - Label and archive Eventbrite event emails
206: - `create-meet-notes-filter.mjs` - Label Google Meet notes
207: - `delete-sentry-filter.mjs` - Remove outdated filters
208: 
209: **Archive & Processing Scripts:**
210: - `archive-signoz-dmarc.mjs` - Batch archive monitoring and DMARC report emails using Gmail batch API
211: - `mark-signoz-read.mjs` - Mark SigNoz alerts as read in bulk
212: - `mark-past-events-read.mjs` - Classify event emails by date and mark past events as read
213: - `protect-important-inbox.mjs` - Label critical items to prevent archiving (payments, rate limits, services)
214: 
215: **Event Management:**
216: - `filter-events-by-date.mjs` - Classify event emails as future (label + keep) or past (label + archive)
217: - `organize-international-house.mjs` - Label and organize International House event emails
218: 
219: **Utilities:**
220: - `lib/gmail-client.mjs` - Authenticated Gmail API client factory. Centralizes OAuth2 init, token validation, and multi-account support:
221:   ```js
222:   import { createGmailClient } from './lib/gmail-client.mjs';
223:   const gmail = createGmailClient(); // Uses ACCOUNT_MODE env var, throws on missing tokens
224:   ```
225: - `lib/gmail-label-utils.mjs` - Label ID resolution (NEW in v1.4.9). Resolves hardcoded label IDs dynamically for account portability:
226:   ```js
227:   import { buildLabelCache, resolveLabelId } from './lib/gmail-label-utils.mjs';
228:   const labelCache = await buildLabelCache(gmail);
229:   const labelId = labelCache.get('Events/Community'); // Dynamic instead of hardcoded Label_N
230:   ```
231:   See [`docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md`](docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md) for complete documentation.
232: - `lib/gmail-batch.mjs` - Batch filter operations for bulk Gmail tasks (10-100x speedup)
233: - `lib/date-based-filter.mjs` - Pure utility for date-based email classification: extracts dates (ISO, US format, text dates, weekday patterns), compares to today, classifies as past/future/unknown. Does not mutate input. Handles dates without year by inferring current or next year.
234: 
235: ## Example Usage
236: 
237: Along with the normal capabilities you would expect for a calendar integration you can also do really dynamic, multi-step processes like:
238: 
239: 1. **Cross-calendar availability**:
240:    ```
241:    Please provide availability looking at both my personal and work calendar for this upcoming week.
242:    I am looking for a good time to meet with someone in London for 1 hr.
243:    ```
244: 
245: 2. Add events from screenshots, images and other data sources:
246:    ```
247:    Add this event to my calendar based on the attached screenshot.
248:    ```
249:    Supported image formats: PNG, JPEG, GIF
250:    Images can contain event details like date, time, location, and description
251: 
252: 3. Calendar analysis:
253:    ```
254:    What events do I have coming up this week that aren't part of my usual routine?
255:    ```
256: 4. Check attendance:
257:    ```
258:    Which events tomorrow have attendees who have not accepted the invitation?
259:    ```
260: 5. Auto coordinate events:
261:    ```
262:    Here's some available that was provided to me by someone. {available times}
263:    Take a look at the times provided and let me know which ones are open on my calendar.
264:    ```
265: 
266: 6. **Gmail workflows**:
267:    ```
268:    How many unread emails do I have from my work account?
269:    ```
270:    ```
271:    Search for all emails from john@company.com that I haven't replied to yet.
272:    ```
273:    ```
274:    Show me all unread messages from the past week.
275:    ```
276:    ```
277:    Mark all unread emails from my boss as read.
278:    ```
279:    ```
280:    Archive all promotional emails from marketing.
281:    ```
282:    ```
283:    Delete these 5 spam messages (provide IDs).
284:    ```
285: 
286: ## Date Parsing
287: 
288: The email organization system uses intelligent date parsing (`lib/date-based-filter.mjs`) to classify event emails:
289: 
290: **Supported Formats:**
291: - ISO 8601: `2026-03-25`, `2026/03/25`
292: - US format: `03/25/2026`, `3/25/2026`
293: - Text format: `March 25, 2026`, `March 25` (infers year)
294: - Weekday patterns: `@ Mon, Mar 23`, `@ Friday Mar 22`
295: - Returns `null` for unparseable dates
296: 
297: **Classification:**
298: - Past events (date < today): archive from inbox, keep label
299: - Future events (date ≥ today): label and keep in inbox
300: - Unknown: marked for manual review
301: 
302: **Implementation Notes:**
303: - Pure function: does not mutate input dates
304: - Handles missing years by inferring current or next year
305: - Used by `mark-past-events-read.mjs` to auto-archive old events
306: 
